The '''Turkestan ground jay''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/n-vireos.html|title=IOC World Bird Names (version 2.3)|editor=Gill, F.|editor2=D. Donsker|year=2009|access-date=27 February 2010}}</ref> '''grey ground jay''' or '''Pander's ground-jay''' ('''''Podoces panderi''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Corvidae|crow and jay]] family, Corvidae. It is found in central Asia, particularly [[Kazakhstan]], [[Turkmenistan]], and [[Uzbekistan]]. More specifically, they tend to be found in [[Astragalus (plant)|Astragalus]], [[Calligonum]] and southern [[Salsola]] vegetation zones.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burnside|first=Robert J.|last2=Brighten|first2=Alex L.|last3=Collar|first3=Nigel J.|last4=Soldatov|first4=Valentin|last5=Koshkin|first5=Maxim|last6=Dolman|first6=Paul M.|last7=Ten|first7=Anna|date=2020-10-01|title=Breeding productivity, nest-site selection and conservation needs of the endemic Turkestan Ground-jay Podoces panderi|journal=Journal of Ornithology|language=en|volume=161|issue=4|pages=1175–1183|doi=10.1007/s10336-020-01790-9|issn=2193-7206|doi-access=free|hdl=2164/18889|hdl-access=free}}</ref> It is closely related to the [[Iranian ground jay]]. Its natural habitat is sandy desert with low shrub cover. It also forages around human settlements and roads.

== Description ==
The Turkestan ground jay is visually similar to the [[Iranian ground jay]], except for its duller, more grayscale coat. {{Convert|25|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length, it has beige-grey upperparts, head, and neck, with a black patch on the throat. They also have a small black patch between their eyes and their black beak, which is slightly decurved.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Madge |first=Steve |date=2020 |title=Turkestan Ground-Jay (Podoces panderi), version 1.0 |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/tugjay1/cur/introduction |journal=Birds of the World |language=en |doi=10.2173/bow.tugjay1.01 |issn=2771-3105|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

